{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:53:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:53:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14768"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14768"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0,0,0.68,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65204"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7459"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50641"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5045"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18266"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65204"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETocolytic medications are used to suppress uterine contractions in pre-term labour. Different drug classes work through distinct mechanisms to achieve this effect.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of nifedipine when used as a tocolytic agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases cyclic adenosine monophosphate levels","Enhances potassium channel opening","Stimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors","Blocks calcium entry into myometrial cells","Inhibits prostaglandin synthesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENifedipine is a calcium channel blocker that works by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking calcium entry into myometrial cells\u003C/strong\u003E. This prevents the calcium-dependent processes required for smooth muscle contraction, thereby inhibiting uterine contractions. It is considered a first-line tocolytic agent due to its effectiveness and favourable safety profile for both mother and foetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other mechanisms are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases cyclic adenosine monophosphate levels\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a downstream effect of beta-2 receptor stimulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances potassium channel opening\u003C/strong\u003E - While some tocolytics may affect potassium channels, this is not the mechanism of nifedipine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of beta-2 agonists like salbutamol\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy blocking L-type calcium channels, nifedipine prevents the calcium influx necessary for myometrial contraction, effectively suppressing uterine activity in pre-term labour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nifedipine acts as a tocolytic by blocking L-type calcium channels in myometrial smooth muscle cells, preventing uterine contractions","Calcium influx is essential for myometrial smooth muscle contraction during labour","Nifedipine is a preferred tocolytic due to its effectiveness and safety profile"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50641"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14768"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50641"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T20:42:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T20:43:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7459"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65204"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"http